Thank you so much for having me come today to introduce this bill, HB 1525.

1302
02:36:33,500 --> 02:36:40,000
I'm introducing this bill to establish a county nursing home capital reserve fund.

1303
02:36:40,000 --> 02:36:46,000
Our county nursing homes are valuable and necessary facilities in our state.

1304
02:36:46,000 --> 02:36:52,500
We have 11 county nursing homes, two of which are in Coloss County.

1305
02:36:52,500 --> 02:37:12,000
While these facilities are not statutorily required, they have long been part of each county's mission to provide health care services to citizens of the county, especially for our elderly population in need of skilled nursing and medical care.

1306
02:37:12,000 --> 02:37:24,000
They provide a home and a place for people to receive nursing care that would otherwise be unavailable to them in their own home.

1307
02:37:24,000 --> 02:37:33,500
And they are an important health care investment and asset to our municipalities, our counties, and to our state.

1308
02:37:33,500 --> 02:37:50,000
With the desire to keep these facilities running and keeping them updated and fully functional for a few counties, we are fast running into maintenance issues and infrastructure as their infrastructure ages out.

1309
02:37:50,000 --> 02:37:59,000
When buildings begin to age out, there are issues with basic infrastructure such as electrical, heating, and plumbing.

1310
02:37:59,000 --> 02:38:08,500
And when maintenance finally becomes a series of band-aids, then it's time to consider renovations and possibly new construction.

1311
02:38:08,500 --> 02:38:10,500
Here's the problem.

1312
02:38:10,500 --> 02:38:18,000
The cost of doing these renovations or new construction has become unmanageable for our counties.

1313
02:38:18,000 --> 02:38:27,500
Counties can no longer determine their own fate with the changes they wish to make when buildings need updating.

1314
02:38:27,500 --> 02:38:48,500
They are at the mercy of federal guidelines, especially the Facilities Guidelines Institute, known as the FGI, which determined for counties the space requirements per resident, as well as for a host of other space requirements for other functions in the facility.

1315
02:38:48,500 --> 02:39:08,500
For example, changes from the 2014 to the 2018 version of FGI added 19 square feet to just one bed space, and when you multiply that to how many beds a facility has, it can mount up quickly in cost.

1316
02:39:08,500 --> 02:39:16,000
Right now, the requirement is for semi-private rooms where two people may share a room.

1317
02:39:16,000 --> 02:39:24,500
You cannot have more people than that, and there are specific requirements for bathroom spaces as well.

1318
02:39:24,500 --> 02:39:33,000
So in any renovation, you have to adhere to these space requirements, and they require a number.

1319
02:39:33,000 --> 02:39:39,500
The FGI also requires a number of bariatric rooms for obese patients too.

1320
02:39:39,500 --> 02:39:53,500
Additionally, it has been noted in a recent preview of their white paper that the next version of FGI will likely require these facilities have private rooms only.

1321
02:39:53,500 --> 02:40:08,000
That being said, we have to also take into account inflation and the cost of labor and materials to do the renovations or new builds in accordance with FGI.

1322
02:40:08,000 --> 02:40:11,000
So what are counties to do?

1323
02:40:11,000 --> 02:40:21,000
They cannot ignore the need for facility upgrades, nor can they continue to put band-aids on infrastructure that's aging out.

1324
02:40:21,000 --> 02:40:36,500
They also don't want to cause county taxes to skyrocket and cause a huge tax burden on citizens, especially since the nursing homes are not the only function that counties provide.

1325
02:40:36,500 --> 02:40:52,000
They also don't want to close the nursing home facilities because people are in need of care, especially as the baby boomer generation is reaching the age of needing these facilities.

1326
02:40:52,000 --> 02:41:08,500
Counties can try and cut renovation or rebuild costs as best, or their rebuild costs as best as possible without compromising quality while adhering to guidelines, but sometimes that just can't be accomplished.

1327
02:41:08,500 --> 02:41:17,500
They also can't go cutting down bed space because that can cause further financial damage to the county.

1328
02:41:17,500 --> 02:41:28,500
So here you have a need to upgrade facilities conflicting with the taxpayers' ability to pay for a very necessary county function.

1329
02:41:28,500 --> 02:41:33,500
This is why counties now need help from the state.

1330
02:41:33,500 --> 02:41:36,500
Our counties are at a crossroads.

1331
02:41:36,500 --> 02:41:50,500
Those counties who are looking to upgrade their facilities can no longer do so for the sums of money that used to be manageable by the county alone.

1332
02:41:50,500 --> 02:42:04,000
The state is in a position to help because of its ability to get grant money from the federal government, as well as income from other sources.

1333
02:42:04,000 --> 02:42:13,000
Now, I know this is an off-budget year, and this is a very challenging ask in this bill.

1334
02:42:13,000 --> 02:42:22,500
But we also have much ARPA money available to be used to help fund this new capital reserve fund.

1335
02:42:22,500 --> 02:42:34,000
