2049
04:22:25,000 --> 04:22:33,500
It made perfect sense to establish a trust for New Hampshire given the situation at the time.

2050
04:22:33,500 --> 04:22:43,000
Stakeholders were told that the states with trusts would receive more money under the basic plus bonus settlement model.

2051
04:22:43,000 --> 04:23:00,000
And this model is a formula that rewards states with a larger settlement amount if they have a trust in place and get political subdivisions to agree to the settlements to avoid further litigation.

2052
04:23:00,000 --> 04:23:12,000
There were 23 political subdivisions here in our state, 10 counties and 13 municipalities, that joined the national litigation prior to September 1st, 2019.

2053
04:23:12,000 --> 04:23:20,500
In the calculation, the base is determined by factors such as each state's population, opioid fatalities, etc.

2054
04:23:20,500 --> 04:23:28,500
And the bonus is determined by the percentage of political subdivisions that agreed to the deal.

2055
04:23:28,500 --> 04:23:37,500
New Hampshire largely followed the 70-15-15 model recommended by the judge presiding over the national litigation in Ohio.

2056
04:23:37,500 --> 04:23:43,500
And 70% goes to the opioid abatement trust established by RSA 126A83.

2057
04:23:43,500 --> 04:23:56,000
And 15% goes to the 23 political subdivisions, again, the 10 counties and 13 municipalities that joined the national litigation prior to September 1st, 2019.

2058
04:23:56,000 --> 04:24:00,500
The default model includes 15% share for the state.

2059
04:24:00,500 --> 04:24:07,000
However, New Hampshire has decided to allocate its 15% portion to the trust.

2060
04:24:07,000 --> 04:24:17,000
So currently, it's 85% to the trust and 15% to the 23 political subdivisions that engaged in the original litigation.

2061
04:24:17,000 --> 04:24:38,500
What I'm proposing today is to make changes to that allocation in order to fix a population penalty and provide a more equitable distribution of settlement dollars to the 23 political subdivisions that represent the front lines in New Hampshire's ongoing opioid crisis.

2062
04:24:38,500 --> 04:24:49,500
These 23 subdivisions already have viable and successful programs that should continue to be funded to combat opioid prevention, addiction, and rehabilitation.

2063
04:24:49,500 --> 04:24:59,000
The population penalty that I referred to happens because of how the population is counted in the current formula.

2064
04:24:59,000 --> 04:25:10,500
Right now, the county share is decreased based on the population of a city or town that also participated in the original litigation.

2065
04:25:10,500 --> 04:25:28,000
So, for example, the population of Manchester and Nashua, which is 109,565 and 86,494 respectively, are deducted from the county population of Hillsborough County, 400,721, before calculating it against the total population in New Hampshire.

2066
04:25:28,000 --> 04:25:32,500
This reduces the county's share of the litigation award.

2067
04:25:32,500 --> 04:25:39,000
Counties are therefore penalized because municipalities in their county joined onto the litigation.

2068
04:25:39,000 --> 04:25:59,500
